Patch: guard smalot/pdfparser against malformed ToUnicode CMap ranges
=====================================================================

Applies to: smalot/pdfparser v2.12.5
File:       src/Smalot/PdfParser/Font.php  (method loadTranslateTable, bfrange offset branch)

WHY
---
Some PDFs contain a malformed ToUnicode CMap that declares an absurd source
range in a `bfrange` block, e.g. `<0000> <FFFFFFFF> <0000>`. smalot iterates
the entire range building a per-code translation table, which allocates
multiple gigabytes and triggers an *uncatchable* PHP memory-exhaustion fatal
(`Allowed memory size ... exhausted @ .../Font.php:240`). Because it is a fatal,
try/catch in DocForge's PdfParser cannot recover from it, so the whole worker
dies and the job fails.

Example trigger: docs/Perera-2021-Applications_of_reinforcement_learning...pdf
Before patch: >1.4 GB and fatal.  After patch: ~68 MB peak, 21k+ words extracted.

FIX
---
Clamp the bfrange source span to a sane maximum (0xFFFF). A legitimate bfrange
stays within a single codespace, so anything wider is malformed and can be
truncated rather than crashing.

`vendor/` is git-ignored and deployed to the host via FTP, so this patch is
applied directly to the deployed file. Re-apply it after any `composer install`
or `composer update` that rewrites Font.php.

DIFF
----
@@ loadTranslateTable(), bfrange "offset" branch @@
                         if (1 === preg_match('/^<(?P<offset>[0-9A-F]+)>$/i', $dest, $offset_matches)) {
                             // Support for : <srcCode1> <srcCode2> <dstString>
                             $offset = hexdec($offset_matches['offset']);

-                            for ($char = $char_from; $char <= $char_to; ++$char) {
+                            // DocForge guard: clamp absurd/malformed source ranges
+                            // (e.g. <0000><FFFFFFFF>) that would build a multi-GB
+                            // table and trigger an uncatchable memory fatal.
+                            $char_to_capped = $char_to;
+                            if ($char_to_capped - $char_from > 0xFFFF) {
+                                $char_to_capped = $char_from + 0xFFFF;
+                            }
+
+                            for ($char = $char_from; $char <= $char_to_capped; ++$char) {
                                 $this->table[$char] = self::uchr($char - $char_from + $offset);
                             }
